      <hedline>
        <hl1>Wash Your Hands (Don't Forget the Soap)</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ian Alterman letter criticizes selfishness of New Yorkers who spread germs by failing to wash their hands after using toilet (Sept 19 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Washing Up Is Down, Study Shows'' (news article, Sept. 19):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Washing Up Is Down, Study Shows'' (news article, Sept. 19):</p>
        <p>You quote a bathroom attendant at Grand Central Terminal as saying: ''The commuter doesn't wash his hands. Then they go out and  get something to eat.'' Or they  rub their eyes. Or touch subway or bus poles. Or shake the hands of clients. Or go to jobs where they handle food.</p>
        <p>Although the American Society for Microbiology correctly warns that consequences could be dire, from an increase in infectious diseases to germs that are increasingly resistant to antibiotics, there is also equally basic problem involved: discourtesy. Not washing one's hands after using a toilet at home, at work or in public is incredibly selfish.</p>
        <p>IAN ALTERMAN  New York, Sept. 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
